<p>This two-family structure reflects a fundamental difference in what
the definitions measure. The S-score, entropy, and Gini all quantify the
concentration of activity across the full kinase panel; they differ in
functional form but respond to the same underlying property of the
binding profile. The ratio definition, by contrast, quantifies the gap
between the primary target and a specific off-target, ignoring the
remainder of the binding profile entirely. A compound that strongly
inhibits one kinase and moderately inhibits twenty others will be ranked
as highly selective by ratio (large gap to the second target) but as
moderately promiscuous by entropy and Gini (activity distributed across
many targets).</p>
<h2 id="rank-instability-is-structured-and-predictable">Rank Instability
Is Structured and Predictable</h2>
<figure id="fig:instability" data-latex-placement="h">
<img src="figures/instability_by_family.png" style="width:85.0%" />
<figcaption>Best predictor of rank instability within each definition
family (Klaeger dataset, active compounds, <span
class="math inline"><em>n</em> = 206</span>). Ratio instability is best
predicted by the top<span
class="math inline"><sub>1</sub></span>–top<span
class="math inline"><sub>2</sub></span> affinity gap; entropy, Gini, and
S-score instability are best predicted by features of the active
affinity distribution.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p><span id="sec:results:instability"
data-label="sec:results:instability"></span></p>
<p>Overall rank instability — measured as the standard deviation of a
compound’s rank across all 30 configurations — varies substantially
across compounds (Klaeger: mean <span
class="math inline"><em>σ</em> = 35.4</span>, range <span
class="math inline">7.1</span>–<span class="math inline">91.6</span>;
Davis: mean <span class="math inline"><em>σ</em> = 8.5</span>, range
<span class="math inline">1.6</span>–<span
class="math inline">19.3</span>). Instability is not uniformly
distributed: within each definition family, specific binding profile
features predict which compounds receive unstable rankings (Table <a
href="#tab:predictors" data-reference-type="ref"
data-reference="tab:predictors">2</a>).</p>
<p>Within the ratio family, the gap between the top and second-ranked
affinities (top<span class="math inline"><sub>1</sub></span>–top<span
class="math inline"><sub>2</sub></span> gap) is the strongest predictor
of instability (<span class="math inline"><em>r</em> = −0.446</span>,
<span class="math inline"><em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</span> on Davis; <span
class="math inline"><em>r</em> = −0.293</span>, <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</span> on Klaeger). Compounds
with near-identical affinities for their two best-bound kinases receive
highly variable ratio rankings because the choice of reference
off-target (<span class="math inline"><em>k</em> = 1</span> vs. <span
class="math inline"><em>k</em> = 2, …, 5</span>) determines whether the
compound appears selective or promiscuous.</p>
<p>Within the entropy and Gini families, the number of active kinases
(<span
class="math inline">p<em>K</em><sub><em>d</em></sub> &gt; 6</span>)
negatively predicts instability (<span
class="math inline"><em>r</em> = −0.279</span>, <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &lt; 0.05</span> for entropy on Davis;
<span class="math inline"><em>r</em> = −0.474</span>, <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</span> on Klaeger). Compounds
with many active kinases have well-defined broad profiles whose entropy
and Gini scores are stable across baseline choices; compounds with few
active kinases are sensitive to the baseline because small changes can
move targets in or out of the active set, altering the distribution
substantially. The active affinity range is also a significant predictor
across all three distribution-based definitions on Klaeger (<span
class="math inline"><em>r</em> = −0.31</span> to <span
class="math inline">−0.37</span>, all <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</span>), consistent with the
interpretation that heterogeneous profiles are easier to rank stably
than flat ones.</p>
<p>S-score instability is not significantly predicted by any profile
feature on either dataset, suggesting that it is driven primarily by
where compounds fall relative to the threshold rather than by intrinsic
profile shape.</p>
