</figure>
<p><span id="sec:results:taxonomy"
data-label="sec:results:taxonomy"></span></p>
<p>Examination of the most and least unstable compounds in the Klaeger
dataset reveals three structurally distinct sources of rank instability,
each implicating a different aspect of how the definitions are
constructed.</p>
<p><strong>Type 1 — Zero-active compounds.</strong> The five most
unstable Klaeger compounds (e.g. AZD-8055, BMS-911543, Filgotinib; rank
<span class="math inline"><em>σ</em> &gt; 80</span>) all have zero
active kinases at the <span
class="math inline">p<em>K</em><sub><em>d</em></sub> &gt; 6</span>
threshold. These compounds have no meaningful binding to any profiled
kinase at sub-micromolar affinity, yet all four definitions still assign
them numerical selectivity scores based on the detection floor values.
The resulting rankings are arbitrary: different parameterizations
produce different orderings of compounds that are, in practice,
indistinguishable from one another. Mean rank instability for
zero-active compounds is <span
class="math inline"><em>σ</em> ≈ 74</span>, compared with <span
class="math inline"><em>σ</em> ≈ 32</span> for compounds with at least
one active kinase (<span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</span>, Mann–Whitney <span
class="math inline"><em>U</em></span> test). This pattern is observed
only in the Klaeger dataset; all Davis compounds have at least one
active kinase, consistent with Davis’s fixed-concentration screening
design, which reports a <span
class="math inline"><em>K</em><sub><em>d</em></sub></span> only when
activity is first detected at 10 <span
class="math inline"><em>μ</em></span>M.</p>
<p><strong>Type 2 — Near-tied top targets.</strong> Among active
compounds, ratio-specific instability is strongly predicted by a small
top<span class="math inline"><sub>1</sub></span>–top<span
class="math inline"><sub>2</sub></span> gap (<span
class="math inline"><em>r</em> = −0.293</span>, <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &lt; 0.001</span>). Compounds such as
Dovitinib (top<span class="math inline"><sub>1</sub></span>–top<span
class="math inline"><sub>2</sub></span> gap <span
class="math inline"> = 1.935</span> pKd units) and BMS-690514 (gap <span
class="math inline"> = 1.985</span>) show large entropy-ratio
disagreement despite having well-defined primary targets, because the
ratio definition is sensitive to whether the reference off-target is the
second or a lower-ranked kinase. By contrast, Drug 23 in the Davis
dataset (top<span class="math inline"><sub>1</sub></span>–top<span
class="math inline"><sub>2</sub></span> gap <span
class="math inline"> = 0.019</span>) shows maximal ratio instability
because its two best-bound kinases are essentially indistinguishable,
making the ratio highly sensitive to which is designated the primary
target.</p>
<p><strong>Type 3 — Broad profiles with a dominant primary
target.</strong> The largest entropy-ratio disagreements in the Klaeger
dataset arise for compounds with high <span
class="math inline"><em>n</em><sub>active</sub></span> and a large
top<span class="math inline"><sub>1</sub></span>–top<span
class="math inline"><sub>2</sub></span> gap (e.g. Dovitinib: <span
class="math inline"><em>n</em><sub>active</sub> = 26</span>, gap <span
class="math inline"> = 1.935</span>; BMS-690514: <span
class="math inline"><em>n</em><sub>active</sub> = 20</span>, gap <span
class="math inline"> = 1.985</span>). These compounds have one clearly
dominant target but also bind many kinases at moderate affinity. The
ratio definition scores them as highly selective (large gap between
primary and secondary target), while the entropy and Gini definitions
score them as moderately promiscuous (activity spread across many
targets). Neither characterization is incorrect; they reflect genuinely
different questions about selectivity.</p>
<p>Conversely, the most stable compounds in both datasets (e.g. XL-228,
<span class="math inline"><em>σ</em> = 7.1</span>; PF-03814735, <span
class="math inline"><em>σ</em> = 8.1</span>) are highly promiscuous,
with 40–57 active kinases. When a compound binds nearly the entire
profiled kinome, all definitions rank it as non-selective regardless of
parameterization, producing low instability despite — or rather because
of — high promiscuity.</p>
<h2 id="sec:results:outcomes">Clinical Outcome Correlations</h2>
<p>Spearman correlations between median selectivity rankings and
FAERS-derived adverse event rates (serious event rate, death rate,
hospitalization rate) across 46 FDA-approved Klaeger compounds were
uniformly weak and non-significant (all <span
class="math inline">|<em>r</em>| &lt; 0.18</span>, all <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &gt; 0.14</span>). Similarly,
correlations between selectivity rankings and FDA label discontinuation
rates due to adverse events (<span
class="math inline"><em>n</em> = 33</span> drugs) were non-significant
across all four definition families (all <span
class="math inline">|<em>r</em>| &lt; 0.27</span>, all <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> &gt; 0.13</span>).</p>
<p>We attribute these null results to confounding inherent in both data
sources rather than absence of a biological relationship between
selectivity and toxicity. FAERS report counts are driven primarily by
prescription volume and indication prevalence rather than drug toxicity
per se; drugs approved for common conditions (e.g. tofacitinib for
rheumatoid arthritis, palbociclib for breast cancer) accumulate large
report counts regardless of their adverse event profiles relative to
alternative therapies. Discontinuation rates from drug labels reflect
the clinical trial populations and indication-specific toxicity
expectations for those populations, making cross-indication comparisons
unreliable. A rigorous test of the relationship between in vitro
selectivity and clinical toxicity would require indication-stratified,
treatment-related adverse event rates from randomized controlled trials
with matched comparators, which are not available in a standardized form
across the breadth of kinase inhibitors studied here.</p>
<h2 id="sec:results:panelsize">Panel Size Dependence of Selectivity
Rankings</h2>
<p>To assess the stability of selectivity rankings as a function of
kinase panel size, we performed a subsampling analysis on the Klaeger
dataset. The Davis dataset was not used for this analysis for two
reasons: its complete matrix design (every compound tested against every
kinase by construction) does not reflect the sparse coverage of real
profiling panels, and subsampling kinases from Davis changes the
apparent number of active compounds in ways that confound the panel size
effect with the zero-active instability characterized in the instability
taxonomy above. The Klaeger dataset, derived from chemoproteomic
dose–response profiling with genuine sparse kinase coverage, is the more
appropriate substrate for this question. For each panel size <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> ∈ {50, 80, …, 320, 343}</span>, we drew
50 random subsets of <span class="math inline"><em>p</em></span> kinases
from the full panel of 343, computed each selectivity definition on the
subpanel, and measured agreement with the full-panel ranking using
Spearman correlation.</p>
<p>The four definitions differ substantially in their panel size
requirements (Figure <a href="#fig:panelsize" data-reference-type="ref"
data-reference="fig:panelsize">3</a>). Selectivity entropy reaches mean
<span class="math inline"><em>r</em> = 0.90</span> against the
full-panel ranking at approximately 110 kinases, and S-score at
approximately 140 kinases. The Gini coefficient requires approximately
290 kinases to reach the same threshold. The ratio definition does not
reach <span class="math inline"><em>r</em> = 0.90</span> until the panel
contains 320 or more kinases, and achieves <span
class="math inline"><em>r</em> = 0.888</span> even at 320 kinases — only
23 below the full panel size.</p>
<p>This result has a direct practical implication. Standard commercial
kinase selectivity panels typically profile 50–100 kinases.<span
class="citation" data-cites="Bosc2017"><sup>[8]</sup></span> At these
panel sizes, entropy- and S-score-based rankings are reasonably stable
(<span class="math inline"><em>r</em> ≈ 0.76</span>–<span
class="math inline">0.85</span>), but Gini and ratio rankings are
effectively uncorrelated with what would be obtained on a full kinome
panel (<span class="math inline"><em>r</em> &lt; 0.14</span> for Gini,
<span class="math inline"><em>r</em> &lt; 0.00</span> for ratio at <span
class="math inline"><em>p</em> = 50</span>). Ratio rankings in
particular are unreliable at any panel size commonly used in practice,
because the identity of the reference off-target (<span
class="math inline"><em>k</em></span>-th ranked kinase) changes
substantially as panel composition changes. This constitutes a fifth
source of evidence that ratio-based definitions measure a qualitatively
different property from distribution-based definitions, and reinforces
D2 (bounded gap sensitivity) as a necessary desideratum.</p>
